Background

  • County COVID-19 dashboards provide crucial public health information to constituents, stakeholders, and policymakers
  • The development of dashboard-related best practices can help health departments optimize the public utility and epidemiologic rigor of their dashboards
  • The implementation of best practices can improve health equity by providing communities with standardized metrics of risk from COVID-19 transmission

Methods

  • Counties were selected using a stratified sampling method
    • Six counties from each region—North, South, East, and West—were included
    • Texas counties were excluded to avoid potential conflicts of interest
  • For the selected counties, researchers found COVID-19 monitoring dashboards which are maintained by a state or county health or government authority
  • Authors researched and compiled 10 factors concerning user friendliness and accessibility and 25 factors concerning the epidemiological completeness of key metrics
    • Dashboards were evaluated using a survey instrument
    • Two authors independently evaluated each dashboard and any discordance between authors’ evaluations was recorded and reconciled
  • Some counties maintain their own COVID-19 dashboards, while many rely on state-maintained COVID-19 monitoring dashboards
    • To accommodate counties which do not maintain their own dashboards, a sample of state dashboards were included in the sample and analyzed at the county-level
    • State (\(n= 9\)) and county (\(n= 15\)) dashboards were examined separately
  • The data collected and presented in this presentation are subject to change

Sample stratification

  • The sample included 24 counties which were uniformly sampled from the four regions of the country (North, South, East, and West)
  • 12 of the sampled counties are classified as rural and 12 are classified as urban
  • The counties were sampled with respect to their poverty rates conditional on their region

Public accessibility

Criteria

  • The dashboards were evaluated across 10 factors concerning the public accessibility of the dashboard
    • Two factors fell into the category: Accessibility
    • Three factors fell into the category: Communication
    • Five factors fell into the category: Data integrity and system quality

Results

  • Lincoln County, NV (a state dashboard) scored the highest (90%) across public accessibility factors
  • Language translation was the most common public accessibility criterion that was not met
    • 83% of dashboards were only available in English
    • The four dashboards which did provide language translation were all translated into Spanish

Public accessibility - Accessibility

Best practices

  • Two indicators were identified as best practices to monitor accessibility
    • Dashboard is interactive
    • Translated into multiple languages

Results - Interactivity

  • 29% of the dashboards were not interactive
    • 33% of county dashboards were not interactive, compared to 22% of state dashboards
  • Four of the dashboards evaluated were PDFs
  • Only two county dashboards and two state dashboards were translated into another language

Results - Language translation

  • The sampled counties contain diverse speaking populations
    • In nine counties, 10% of the county population primarily speaks a language besides English at home
  • In three counties, 25% of the county population primarily speaks Spanish at home
    • Of these three counties, only one dashboards provided a Spanish translation

Public accessibility - Communication

Best practices

  • Three indicators were identified as best practices to monitor communication
    • Dashboard provides definitions of epidemiological terms/indicators
    • County level risk score is shown
    • Documentation is provided on how risk score links to epidemiological indicators

Results - Epidemiologic terms and indicators

  • Many dashboards could have included more documentation of epidemiological terminology and indicators
    • Overall, only 50% dashboards included explanations of epidemiological terminology and indicators
  • This percentage differed between state- and county- maintained dashboards
    • 27% of county dashboards included explanations of their terminology compared to 89% of state dashboards
Allegheny county, PA county dashboard

Public accessibility - Communication

Results - County risk score

  • The majority of the sample did not have a color-coded risk system in place to communicate overall risk level to the public
    • 38% of the dashboards have a color-coded risk system
    • This percentage was identical for county- and state-maintained dashboards
Coconino County, AZ county dashboard

Results - Linking risk score to epidemiological indicators

  • Of the dashboard which included a color-coded risk score, 78% of the dashboards provided documentation on how the color-coded risk system is linked to the epidemiological indicators
    • This percentage did not differ significantly between dashboards maintained by the county or the state
Nevada state dashboard

Public accessibility - Data integrity and system quality

Best practices

  • Five indicators were identified as best practices to monitor data integrity and system quality
    • Data sources are clearly labeled
    • Data sources are a county or state public health authority
    • Date the data were last updated is clearly labeled
    • Data were last updated within the last 2 days or less
    • A member of the public can download the data

Results - Data integrity

  • All dashboards were hosted by an official county or state government authority
    • 27% of county dashboards were hosted by the county public health authority, while 78% of state dashboards were hosted by the state public health authority
  • While many of the dashboards are hosted by public health authorities, only 45.8% of dashboards explicitly labeled their data source
    • Of the dashboards which were not hosted by state or county public health authorities, only 54% explicitly labeled their data source

Results - Data system quality

  • The vast majority (92%) of dashboards clearly labeled the date their data were last updated
  • 83% of dashboards update their data regularly (within two days of review), with similar percentages for state and county dashboards
    • All of these dashboards regularly update case data, while 90% update deaths data and 71% update testing data
  • The four counties that did not update their data within two days of review update their data weekly
  • Only six (25%) of dashboards allow the user to download the data
    • Five of these are state dashboards

Epidemiological completeness

Criteria

  • The dashboards were evaluated across 25 factors concerning their epidemiological rigor
    • 12 factors fell into the category: Disease situation
    • 11 factors fell into the category: Disease control
    • Two factors fell into the category: Health care system

Results

  • Allegheny County, PA (a county dashboard) scored the highest (52%) across epidemiology completeness factors
  • The most commonly reported metric was daily new cases at the county level
    • However, only 58.3% of dashboards reported this metric
  • None of the dashboards in this sample reported median/average time from specimen collection to isolation of cases, percent of new cases epidemiologically linked to at least one other case, median/average diagnostic test turnaround time, or daily COVID-19 hospitalizations as a moving average
  • The average percent of criteria met did not differ between county- and state-maintained dashboards (22.5% vs 23.7%)

Epidemiological completeness - Disease situation

Best practices - Cases

  • Four indicators were identified as best practices to monitor case incidence
    • Dashboard reports daily new cases at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily new cases per capita at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily new cases with a moving average at the county level
    • Dashboard reports confirmed and probable cases at the county level

Results

  • 58% of dashboards reported daily COVID-19 cases at the county level
    • In our sample, a higher proportion of county dashboards (66.7%) reported daily COVID-19 cases at the county level than state dashboards (44%)
  • Fewer dashboards reported the metric daily COVID-19 cases with a moving average at the county level (33%) and the metric daily COVID-19 cases per capita at the county level (8%)
    • Only two dashboards reported all three case indicators

Alternative ways to display case incidence

  • Several dashboards still report cumulative cases at the weekly level or cumulative case counts for the county
  • Several of the state dashboards provide a graph showing daily COVID-19 cases but do not provide users with the ability to drill down to their county
Case data for Baldwin County, Georgia state dashboard

Epidemiological completeness - Disease situation

Best practices - Demographics

  • Four best practices were identified to monitor demographic characteristics
    • Dashboard reports case data stratified by any demographics (e.g. sex, race/ethnicity, age) at the county level
    • Dashboard reports testing data stratified by any demographics (e.g. sex, race/ethnicity, age) at the county level
    • Dashboard reports test positivity rate stratified by any demographics (e.g. sex, race/ethnicity, age) at the county level
    • Dashboard reports deaths data stratified by any demographics (e.g., sex, race/ethnicity, age) at the county level

Results - Cases

  • Out of 24 dashboards, 58% stratified cases by age, sex, or race/ethnicity
  • In this sample it was more common for county dashboards to report demographic information that state dashboards (67% vs 44%)
  • Some dashboards stratified deaths by demographics, but did not regularly update their demographic data

Results - Testing and test positivity rate

  • 83% of dashboards did not include any testing demographics
  • Very few dashboards stratified the test positivity rate by any demographic characteristics (17%)
    • This percentage was similar for both county and state dashboards

Results - Mortality

  • It was not common for dashboards to stratify mortality by demographics
    • 33% stratified cases by age, sex, or race/ethnicity
    • Slightly more county dashboards reported demographic information as state dashboards, 38% vs 25%, respectively

Epidemiological completeness - Disease situation

Best practices - Syndromic surveillance

  • Two indicators were identified as best practices to monitor syndromic surveillance trends
    • Dashboard reports COVID Like Illness (CLI) trends at the county level
    • Dashboard reports Influenza Like Illness (ILI) trends at the county level

Results

  • It was uncommon for county and state dashboards to report syndromic surveillance indicators
    • Three reported CLI and only one reported ILI
    • Two dashboards linked to separate reports where the CLI and ILI were monitored for their region
Carroll County, MS state dashboard

Epidemiological completeness - Disease situation

Best practices - Mortality

  • Four indicators were identified as best practices to monitor mortality
    • Dashboard reports daily deaths at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily deaths per capita at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily deaths with a moving average at the county level
    • Dashboard reports confirmed and probable deaths at the county level

Results

  • Although the majority of dashboards included some indicator of COVID-19 mortality at the county level (20 dashboards), only a few contained the above best practices
  • Seven dashboards reported daily deaths, daily deaths per capita, or daily deaths as a moving average
    • Six dashboards reported daily deaths
    • Two dashboards reported deaths per capita
    • Four dashboards reported deaths with moving averages
    • Six dashboards explicitly reported both confirmed and probable deaths

Alternative ways to display mortality

  • State and county dashboards commonly reported mortality data as a cumulative count
    • 11 dashboards displayed their data as a cumulative count
    • Two dashboards displayed their data as a cumulative weekly count

Epidemiological completeness - Disease control

Best practices - Testing

  • Four indicators were identified as best practices to monitor testing
    • Dashboard reports daily total testing at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily total testing with a moving average at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily test positivity at the county level
    • Dashboard reports daily test positivity with a moving average at the county level
Allegheny county, PA county dashboard

Results

  • Overall, the majority of dashboards (75%) included some level of information on COVID-19 testing at the county level
    • The percentage of dashboards reporting testing data was similar between county and state dashboards
  • However, only 33% included information on daily testing at the county level
    • 22% of dashboards reported data on daily testing with a moving average, with a slightly greater percentage of state dashboards reporting this metric (29% vs. 18%)
  • 44.4% of dashboards included information on daily test positivity at the county level
    • 22% of dashboards reported data on daily test positivity with a moving average, with a greater percentage of state dashboards reporting this metric (29% vs. 18%)
  • Only two dashboards reported all of the above metrics

Epidemiological completeness - Disease control

Best practices - Congregate facilities

  • One best practice was identified to monitor outbreaks in congregate care settings
    • Dashboard includes any data about cases or deaths at long-term care and congregate facilities at the county level
North Dakota state dashboard
Franklin County, NY county dashboard

Results

  • Dashboards did not commonly report data on case outbreaks and deaths in congregate care facilities at the county level
    • Only three dashboards reported any data on congregate care facilities at the county level
    • One dashboard provided data on cases/outbreaks within correctional facilities at the county level
    • Three dashboards provided data on cases/outbreaks within long-term care facilities
    • Three dashboards provided data on deaths within long-term care facilities
  • Some dashboards did report data on case outbreaks and death, but they were either:
    • Not specific to congregate care facilities
    • Not at the county-level
  • In the sample, none of the dashboards reported cases or outbreaks among homeless shelters or essential workplaces (e.g. the meatpacking industry)

Epidemiological completeness - Disease control

Best practices - Contact tracing

  • Two best practices were identified to monitor contract tracing
    • Dashboard reports median/average time from specimen collection to isolation of cases by week reported at the county level
    • Dashboard reports the % of new cases epidemiologically linked to at least one other case

Results

  • It was not common for dashboards to report on contract tracing metrics
    • None of the dashboards in our sample reported median/average time from specimen collection to isolation of cases by week reported at the county level
    • None of the dashboards in our sample reported the % of new cases epidemiologically linked to at least one other case
Tompkins County, NY county dashboard

Epidemiological completeness - Health care system

Best practices

  • Two best practices were identified to monitor hospitalizations
    • Dashboard reports daily COVID-19 hospitalizations as a moving average at the county or regional level
    • Dashboard reports daily % of licensed beds occupied by COVID-19 (confirmed or suspected) positive cases at the county or regional level

Results

  • While most dashboards did not report either of those specific metrics, many dashboards did report additional data on hospitalizations or hospital system utilization (54.2%)

Conclusion

Health equity

  • Significant gains in health equity could be made by standardizing metrics and risk thresholds and updating monitoring dashboards accordingly
  • In many cases, health equity could also be improved if counties expanded demographic stratification beyond case incidence
  • Counties should also monitor access to testing and severe outcomes such as hospitalization and deaths among different demographics

Public accessibility

  • Many counties could improve the usability of their dashboards by including a color-coded risk threshold system with clear documentation about how the risk levels are linked to current indicators of COVID-19 community transmission
  • Counties should consider adding multiple language options or providing key metrics in multiple languages to improve equitable access to information
  • If possible, dashboard developers should automate data updates to ensure that data are updated regularly and not just on weekdays

Epidemiological completeness

  • A range of indicators should be used to assess disease situation, control, and the state of the health care system
  • These indicators should be provided as per capita rates and with moving averages to be able to easily compare to other jurisdictions and time periods
  • Indicators should be expanded to include indicators of syndromic surveillance and hospital capacity
